<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-16 sm:py-24">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400">Docs / Integration</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-50 md:text-5xl">
        Connect an LLM
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400">
        emisar exposes your action catalog as an MCP-style HTTP tool API so
        LLMs can call <em>exactly</em> the actions your team has declared —
        nothing more. This page walks through the three things you need:
        an API key, a tool list, and a tool call.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-12 space-y-12">
        <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
        <%!-- Step 1: API key                                              --%>
        <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
        <section>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="grid h-8 w-8 place-items-center rounded-full bg-indigo-500/20 text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-300">1</span>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-50">Issue an API key</h2>
          </div>

          <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
            In the dashboard go to <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-sm">Settings → API keys</code>
            and click <strong>Issue an API key</strong>. Two things matter:
          </p>

          <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-zinc-300">
            <li class="flex gap-3">
              <.icon name="hero-check" class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-none text-indigo-400" />
              <div>
                <strong>Scopes</strong> — tick <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">actions:read</code>
                and <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">actions:execute</code>.
                Add <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">audit:read</code>
                if the LLM should be able to read run history.
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="flex gap-3">
              <.icon name="hero-check" class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-none text-indigo-400" />
              <div>
                <strong>Allowed runners</strong> — leave empty to allow every
                runner, or tick the specific runners the key may target. We
                strongly recommend the explicit list for production keys.
              </div>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            The dashboard reveals the raw key <em>once</em>. Copy it now and
            store it in your secret manager.
          </p>
        </section>

        <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
        <%!-- Step 2: list tools                                           --%>
        <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
        <section>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="grid h-8 w-8 place-items-center rounded-full bg-indigo-500/20 text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-300">2</span>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-50">List the tools</h2>
          </div>

          <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
            One GET away. The response is JSON; each tool has a name, a
            human-readable description, and a JSON-schema-shaped
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-sm">inputSchema</code>
            so the model can validate args locally before calling.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-4 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
            <div class="border-b border-zinc-900 px-3 py-2 font-mono text-[11px] text-zinc-500">terminal</div>
<pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> curl https://app.emisar.com/api/mcp/tools \
    -H <span class="text-emerald-300">"Authorization: Bearer $EMISAR_API_KEY"</span></pre>
          </div>
        </section>

        <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
        <%!-- Step 3: call a tool                                          --%>
        <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
        <section>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="grid h-8 w-8 place-items-center rounded-full bg-indigo-500/20 text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-300">3</span>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-50">Call a tool</h2>
          </div>

          <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
            Pass <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-sm">?wait=15s</code>
            (max <code>60s</code>) to get the result inline, or omit it for fire-and-forget.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-4 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
            <div class="border-b border-zinc-900 px-3 py-2 font-mono text-[11px] text-zinc-500">terminal</div>
<pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500"># Synchronous: long-poll up to 15 seconds for the result.</span>
<span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> curl -X POST <span class="text-emerald-300">"https://app.emisar.com/api/mcp/tools/linux.uptime?wait=15s"</span> \
    -H <span class="text-emerald-300">"Authorization: Bearer $EMISAR_API_KEY"</span> \
    -H <span class="text-emerald-300">"Content-Type: application/json"</span> \
    -d <span class="text-emerald-300">'&#123;"args": &#123;&#125;&#125;'</span></pre>
          </div>

          <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            The response includes the final
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">status</code>,
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">exit_code</code>,
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">stdout</code> (last 64 KiB),
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">stderr</code>,
            and the
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">policy</code>
            decision that allowed/gated the call. If the run needs approval,
            the response is HTTP 202 with
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">status: "pending_approval"</code>
            — the LLM can surface that to the user and poll
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">GET /api/mcp/runs/:id</code>
            to wait for the operator decision.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>

      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <%!-- Per-client setup                                             --%>
      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <h2 class="mt-20 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-50">Per-client setup</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
        We ship a tiny stdio bridge — <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar-mcp</code> —
        for clients that speak the MCP JSON-RPC protocol natively
        (Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, Gemini CLI, Codex CLI). For
        OpenAI tool calling and other HTTP-only clients, hit the JSON API
        directly.
      </p>

      <%!-- Install the bridge --%>
      <section class="mt-8">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Install the bridge</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
          The <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar-mcp</code>
          binary runs on the same machine as your editor / chat client — your
          laptop. It launches as a child process and proxies MCP JSON-RPC
          requests to the emisar HTTP API. Two install paths:
        </p>

        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-zinc-300">
          <strong>Option 1 — from a GitHub release</strong> (recommended once tagged builds exist):
        </p>
        <div class="mt-2 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
          <div class="border-b border-zinc-900 px-3 py-2 font-mono text-[11px] text-zinc-500">terminal</div>
<pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500"># Pick the right OS/arch for your laptop (linux-amd64, linux-arm64,</span>
<span class="text-zinc-500"># darwin-amd64, darwin-arm64). Each release tarball contains both</span>
<span class="text-zinc-500"># `emisar` (the runner) and `emisar-mcp` (the bridge).</span>
<span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> curl -sSL <span class="text-emerald-300">https://github.com/andrewdryga/emisar/releases/latest/download/emisar-vX.Y.Z-darwin-arm64.tar.gz</span> \
    | tar -xz --strip-components=1 -C /tmp emisar-vX.Y.Z-darwin-arm64/emisar-mcp
<span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> sudo install -m 0755 /tmp/emisar-mcp /usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp</pre>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-zinc-300">
          <strong>Option 2 — <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">go install</code></strong>
          (requires Go 1.26+; useful while we're pre-release):
        </p>
        <div class="mt-2 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
          <div class="border-b border-zinc-900 px-3 py-2 font-mono text-[11px] text-zinc-500">terminal</div>
<pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> go install github.com/andrewdryga/emisar/mcp@latest
<span class="text-zinc-500"># Binary lands in $(go env GOBIN) — usually ~/go/bin/emisar-mcp.</span>
<span class="text-zinc-500"># If your client config below uses /usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp, adjust</span>
<span class="text-zinc-500"># the path — or symlink it:</span>
<span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> sudo ln -s ~/go/bin/emisar-mcp /usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp</pre>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-zinc-400">
          Verify with <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar-mcp --help</code>
          (it should print the JSON-RPC subset it implements and exit).
          Note: this is the <em>only</em> binary you need on your laptop;
          the <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar</code> runner
          goes on the Linux hosts you manage, via <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">install.sh</code>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-10">
        <%!-- Claude Desktop --%>
        <section>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Claude Desktop</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Install <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar-mcp</code>
            (the stdio bridge — ships in our GitHub releases) and add this
            to <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json</code>:
          </p>
          <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
            <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300">&#123;
  "mcpServers": &#123;
    "emisar": &#123;
      "command": "/usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp",
      "env": &#123;
        "EMISAR_URL": "https://app.emisar.com",
        "EMISAR_API_KEY": "emk-..."
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</pre>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Restart Claude Desktop. Your action catalog appears under the
            tool icon as "emisar".
          </p>
        </section>

        <%!-- Cursor --%>
        <section>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Cursor</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Same bridge. Cursor reads
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/.cursor/mcp.json</code>:
          </p>
          <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
            <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300">&#123;
  "mcpServers": &#123;
    "emisar": &#123;
      "command": "emisar-mcp",
      "env": &#123;
        "EMISAR_URL": "https://app.emisar.com",
        "EMISAR_API_KEY": "emk-..."
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</pre>
          </div>
        </section>

        <%!-- Claude Code (CLI) --%>
        <section>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Claude Code</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            One command registers the bridge with the Claude Code CLI
            globally (user scope). It will be available in every project.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
            <div class="border-b border-zinc-900 px-3 py-2 font-mono text-[11px] text-zinc-500">terminal</div>
<pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> claude mcp add emisar /usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp \
    --scope user \
    -e EMISAR_URL=https://app.emisar.com \
    -e EMISAR_API_KEY=emk-...</pre>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Verify with <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">claude mcp list</code>.
            Drop <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">--scope user</code>
            to register it only for the current project (writes to
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">.mcp.json</code>).
          </p>
        </section>

        <%!-- Gemini CLI --%>
        <section>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Gemini CLI</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Google's Gemini CLI reads
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/.gemini/settings.json</code>:
          </p>
          <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
            <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300">&#123;
  "mcpServers": &#123;
    "emisar": &#123;
      "command": "/usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp",
      "env": &#123;
        "EMISAR_URL": "https://app.emisar.com",
        "EMISAR_API_KEY": "emk-..."
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</pre>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Inside a Gemini session, <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">/mcp</code>
            lists registered servers and their tools.
          </p>
        </section>

        <%!-- ChatGPT Codex CLI --%>
        <section>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">ChatGPT Codex CLI</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            OpenAI's Codex CLI reads
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/.codex/config.toml</code>.
            Add a server block:
          </p>
          <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
<pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300">[mcp_servers.emisar]
command = "/usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp"
env = &#123; EMISAR_URL = "https://app.emisar.com", EMISAR_API_KEY = "emk-..." &#125;</pre>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Restart Codex. Tools appear under the <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar</code> server.
          </p>
        </section>

        <%!-- OpenAI tool calling --%>
        <section>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">OpenAI tool calling</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            OpenAI doesn't speak MCP, so the integration is a small Python
            shim: pull <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">/api/mcp/tools</code>,
            transform each <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">inputSchema</code>
            into an OpenAI <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">functions[]</code>
            entry, and when the model returns a function call, POST it to
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">/api/mcp/tools/:name?wait=30s</code>.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
            <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500"># Roughly:</span>
tools = requests.get(URL + "/api/mcp/tools", headers=auth).json()["tools"]
functions = [&#123;"type": "function", "function": &#123;
  "name": t["name"],
  "description": t["description"],
  "parameters": t["inputSchema"]&#125;&#125; for t in tools]

resp = openai.responses.create(model="gpt-5", input=..., tools=functions)
for call in resp.tool_calls:
    r = requests.post(URL + f"/api/mcp/tools/&#123;call.name&#125;?wait=30s",
                      headers=auth, json=&#123;"args": call.arguments&#125;)
    feed_back_to_model(r.json())</pre>
          </div>
        </section>

        <%!-- Generic HTTP --%>
        <section>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Generic HTTP / your own agent</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Everything is just JSON. List tools, call a tool, poll the run
            id. The
            <.link href={~p"/docs"} class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300">docs</.link>
            have the full endpoint reference.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
